    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1511663049" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1511663049" />
    <a title="Tamaraa1903" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50333516-tamaraa1903"><img alt="Tamaraa1903" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464475635p2/50333516.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1511663049?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tamaraa1903" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tamaraa1903" href="/user/show/50333516-tamaraa1903">Tamaraa1903</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781860468902" href="/book/show/232071.Ports_of_Call">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50333516-tamaraa1903?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1511663049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3748646421953229971">“Are you certain that a man&apos;s life begins with his birth?”<br/><br/>This is a story of how Ossyane, meaning “Rebellion”, tells his story to a woman that recognized him on the train from the newspapers-but I’ll get to that later. Ossyane had an important event he had to attend in four days, but he agreed on telling the journalist as much as he can.<br/><br/>As Ossyane says at the beginning, this story starts way before his birth. Ossyane’s story begins with his grandmother being the daughter of the Sultan during the</span>
  <span id="freeText3748646421953229971" style="display:none">“Are you certain that a man's life begins with his birth?”<br /><br />This is a story of how Ossyane, meaning “Rebellion”, tells his story to a woman that recognized him on the train from the newspapers-but I’ll get to that later. Ossyane had an important event he had to attend in four days, but he agreed on telling the journalist as much as he can.<br /><br />As Ossyane says at the beginning, this story starts way before his birth. Ossyane’s story begins with his grandmother being the daughter of the Sultan during the Ottoman era. Iffet, Ossyane’s grandmother, becomes mentally ill after some incidents. Iffet’s mother calls the family doctor, and after days of thinking, they agree on one solution: the doctor was going to take Iffet away from the city to Adana, a city in Turkey, for her treatment. Eventually, this ends up with their marriage and their son.<br /><br />The book shortly talks about Ossyane’s father; his education, and his closest friend, who eventually witnesses his sister’s marriage with him. Only then does Ossyane start his life story. You might be wondering why a father would give his child a name such as “Rebellion”. It’s simple; throughout Ossyane’s whole life, his father has been putting pressure on him to be rebellious and revolutionary. Ossyane, however, has other plans for his future-becoming a doctor, just like his grandfather. He convinces his father to move to France to study on his own, and that happens around 1939, when the war breaks out in Europe. Somehow Ossyane unintentionally finds himself in a group of people who fight against the Nazis and the war. The events that follow make him famous for his rebellious actions on several newspapers. When he gets back home, he sees a prodigious crowd waiting for him to come back; in that crowd, he spots his father, who must’ve been very proud, he assumes. He is right. <br /><br />By the time he is back, Ossyane has met a girl in France (from his rebellious group), and they eventually get married. This makes his father even happier. Unfortunately, the only problem that follows is that Ossyane has a brother, who just got out of prison, and decided that he could stay in his father’s house-his father however, does not approve, after what he’s done. Ossyane and his wife decide to take a break and visit the wife’s uncle. During that time, Ossyane’s father dies. This affects Ossyane, and his brother takes over the house. Because his brother wants to keep all his father’s wills to himself, he sends Ossyane to a mental hospital. We don’t just hear what happens in the hospital, but outside as well. Soon, Ossyane finds out that he has a daughter, who by the way is both Muslim and Jewish, that he’s never seen because his wife is scared to visit him.<br /><br />This is a book about how a man became a small part of history, and ended up being in a mental hospital. Now as I said, Ossyane met the journalist on a train, because he had an important meeting in four days. To find out what the meeting was about, you’re going to have to read this amazing story of how Ossyane’s life came to this point. Even though the review might seem a little confusing, this book is the kind of book you’re going to have the “what’s next?!” feeling. Personally, I’ve never read a book like this; the author makes you feel like you’re the journalist interviewing Ossyane, and the events in the book, especially the ending, make you wish you were a part of the story.<br /><br />This book not only highly entertains you, but also gives you an idea of the feud between Turkey and Armenia, which still continues, and how some people got over that feud with love. I highly recommend this book to realistic fiction lovers, with a bit of revolution and romance in it; or to anyone who wants to hear a good story. It has about 209 pages that fly by really fast. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3748646421953229971" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


